WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.000
Good afternoon. My name is Anton Kalabin. I am the owner of several companies and an advisor to strategic management of a number of large companies in Russia.

00:10.000 --> 00:22.000
When we think about how to manage business or any other human community as effectively as possible, the word charisma is very often used.

00:22.000 --> 00:26.000
And today we will talk about charisma, about leadership.

00:26.000 --> 00:36.000
When people say the word charisma, there is often a complete misunderstanding. Everyone means their own thing under this word.

00:36.000 --> 00:48.000
In general, if you look at the historical retrospective, then charisma is an ancient Greek word that takes its origin in church practice.

00:48.000 --> 00:53.000
In Greek, charisma is translated as a gift from God.

00:53.000 --> 01:12.000
In church analogues, it is described that each person has a gift from God from birth, which includes his or her personality, ability to perform various specific actions.

01:12.000 --> 01:25.000
It is claimed that if a person is endowed with some divine gift, then he must use it for his purpose. And not using God's gift, charisma, is a sin.

01:25.000 --> 01:34.000
From this point of view, the approach is very correct. It motivates people to use it if they succeed.

01:34.000 --> 01:39.000
Max Weber introduced a slightly different definition of charisma in scientific practice.

01:39.000 --> 01:48.000
Under charisma, he meant a person who possessed an exceptional set of supernatural qualities.

01:49.000 --> 02:06.000
Thus, according to Max Weber, people, seeing or attributing to a person exceptional qualities, were ready to follow this person wherever he would say, obey his orders without any additional motivators.

02:07.000 --> 02:18.000
Now, when people say the word charisma, there is often a confusion with the public, with the fame, with the qualities of a showman.

02:18.000 --> 02:28.000
Of course, and we will analyze this a little later, the ability to communicate in public is generally one of the necessary qualities of a leader.

02:28.000 --> 02:37.000
However, it is not decisive. If a person is famous and public, it does not mean that he is charismatic. But this is my opinion.

02:37.000 --> 02:41.000
Let's try to approach this issue from a scientific point of view.

02:41.000 --> 02:49.000
Most people, when they start to discuss what charisma is and what to do with it, make a standard mistake.

02:50.000 --> 03:00.000
They begin to argue about the structure of this phenomenon without setting its functionality, without naming, without defining the circle of phenomena that this term describes.

03:00.000 --> 03:16.000
Such a definition in science is called functional. And only by defining the circle of phenomena that we call this term, we can proceed to the study of how it all happens, what this phenomenon consists of.

03:17.000 --> 03:23.000
The internal structure of a phenomenon is described by a structural definition.

03:23.000 --> 03:41.000
And only after we assign this phenomenon, this term, to the functional, we have defined its internal structure, only after that we can start research work to be able to predict how this phenomenon will happen in the future.

03:42.000 --> 03:49.000
That is, we start making a model. The third definition is called a model.

03:49.000 --> 03:58.000
Let's see how this approach works in the description of such a well-known phenomenon as electricity.

03:59.000 --> 04:08.000
When the ancient Greeks first encountered the phenomenon of electricity, they called it the word electro.

04:08.000 --> 04:10.000
Electro from the ancient Greek entary.

04:10.000 --> 04:24.000
That is, they simply assigned a certain term to what they observed, the phenomenon of the attraction of woolen hairs to the entary after they were lost from each other.

04:25.000 --> 04:32.000
Having designated this circle of phenomena, they were able to understand what it consists of.

04:32.000 --> 04:41.000
They began to describe. As a result, it became possible to study what materials can be lost from each other so that this phenomenon occurs, what materials cannot.

04:41.000 --> 04:44.000
That is, when this phenomenon occurs, when it does not.

04:45.000 --> 04:54.000
After a large enough empirical material was accumulated, people began to come up with various hypotheses, to give model definitions.

04:54.000 --> 04:59.000
At first, the models were quite primitive.

04:59.000 --> 05:07.000
The hypothesis was that electricity is some liquid that flows from one substance to another.

05:08.000 --> 05:16.000
Now we are working with the model definition that electricity is a stream of charged particles.

05:16.000 --> 05:23.000
And the presence of these particles, their concentration in a certain physical body, determines its electrical properties.

05:23.000 --> 05:32.000
If we talk about charisma, then it is important for us to first determine what functionality this word describes.

05:38.000 --> 05:44.000
If we give a strict scientific definition of functionality, it will sound as follows.

05:44.000 --> 05:53.000
Charisma is the ability to influence people through positive social motivation.

05:53.000 --> 05:55.000
And now a few words about what it means.

05:55.000 --> 06:00.000
Motivation is the incitement of people to do something.

06:00.000 --> 06:08.000
In this case, the word positive social motivation indicates that we do not consider material motivation.

06:08.000 --> 06:15.000
That is, we say that this is not a commodity-money relationship, not a relationship of paid with the deed.

06:15.000 --> 06:24.000
When we talk about positive social motivation, we say that this is not a compulsion, that is, it is not the use of violence.

06:25.000 --> 06:34.000
If a person uses violence to force another person to do something, he uses social motivation, that is, he does not pay him.

06:34.000 --> 06:40.000
He does not pay in any way, no matter whether with material or other resources.

06:40.000 --> 06:45.000
But at the same time, he acts through negative social motivation, he forces him.

06:46.000 --> 06:54.000
So, charisma is the ability to influence people through positive social motivation.

06:54.000 --> 06:59.000
I would like to draw your attention to the fact that the word ability is used here.

06:59.000 --> 07:05.000
And here we can divide two extremely important concepts, which are very often confused, by the way.

07:05.000 --> 07:07.000
Leadership and charisma.

07:07.000 --> 07:15.000
So, charisma is a potential, it is an ability to influence, and leadership is the process itself.

07:15.000 --> 07:20.000
That is, it is impossible to be a leader without charisma.

07:20.000 --> 07:24.000
However, you can have charisma and not be a leader.

07:24.000 --> 07:32.000
A charismatic person, who is able to potentially influence people, may not use this potential if he does not want to.

07:32.000 --> 07:36.000
He may hide and not show his leadership qualities.

07:36.000 --> 07:40.000
So, leadership is a process of influence.

07:40.000 --> 07:47.000
Naturally, here we are also talking about influence through positive social motivation.

07:47.000 --> 07:53.000
All other influence is no longer leadership, it is another way of managing people.

07:53.000 --> 07:59.000
So, leadership is a process of influence through positive social motivation.

07:59.000 --> 08:05.000
Accordingly, a leader in this approach is a subject of influence.

08:05.000 --> 08:09.000
That is, the one who actually carries out the process of leadership.

08:09.000 --> 08:10.000
Actor.

08:10.000 --> 08:18.000
If we try to reformulate the definition of charisma a little and make it simpler and more understandable,

08:18.000 --> 08:22.000
the definition of charisma will sound as follows.

08:22.000 --> 08:26.000
This is the definition that I use in my practice all the time.

08:26.000 --> 08:31.000
Charisma is the ability to persuade and lead.

08:31.000 --> 08:39.000
By working with this definition, we can move on to the structural definition of charisma.

08:39.000 --> 08:43.000
We need to understand what properties this phenomenon has.

08:43.000 --> 08:47.000
In fact, there are not so many important properties for us.

08:47.000 --> 08:50.000
There are only three.

08:51.000 --> 08:56.000
The first property is visible from the definition that we have just made.

08:56.000 --> 08:59.000
This is the dual nature of charisma.

08:59.000 --> 09:02.000
Look carefully at the previous definition.

09:02.000 --> 09:04.000
It consists of two parts.

09:04.000 --> 09:07.000
The first part is the ability to persuade.

09:07.000 --> 09:10.000
The second part is the ability to lead.

09:11.000 --> 09:20.000
Now try to remember several people you know who can persuade but cannot lead.

09:28.000 --> 09:37.000
Most likely, people who can persuade and cannot lead will be people who can be called specialists,

09:38.000 --> 09:41.000
scientists, advisors, consultants.

09:41.000 --> 09:47.000
Now try to remember people, maybe not even your close friends,

09:47.000 --> 09:56.000
but some famous people who can persuade almost no one, but can lead well.

09:56.000 --> 10:04.000
Most likely, politicians, sports team captains, agitators of all kinds will come here.

10:05.000 --> 10:16.000
Now try to remember people who can persuade and lead.

10:16.000 --> 10:19.000
Most likely, there are not so many people you can remember.

10:19.000 --> 10:24.000
And almost all of them can be combined in one word.

10:24.000 --> 10:26.000
These are leaders.

10:26.000 --> 10:31.000
These leaders can be business leaders, political or public.

10:31.000 --> 10:42.000
But we can call those people who can persuade and lead.

10:42.000 --> 10:45.000
One shoulder does not work.

10:45.000 --> 10:50.000
Only if both shoulders are included, then a leader appears.

10:50.000 --> 10:53.000
A person who can be called by this word.

10:53.000 --> 11:00.000
The second characteristic of charisma, which is no less important than the first, is its relativity.

11:00.000 --> 11:06.000
You can evaluate whether a person is charismatic or not by your experience.

11:06.000 --> 11:13.000
We can judge only when we have a pair that interacts, a person and his audience.

11:13.000 --> 11:18.000
Without asking the audience, we cannot say whether a person is charismatic or not.

11:18.000 --> 11:25.000
Only when we know who we measure this quality with, we can say this.

11:26.000 --> 11:31.000
In the definition of charisma, there is a word influence.

11:31.000 --> 11:35.000
This is someone, a subject, who influences someone.

11:35.000 --> 11:43.000
Until there is at least one of these parts, we cannot say whether this ability exists or not.

11:44.000 --> 11:55.000
Therefore, the term is usually used for politicians who work with a large electorate.

11:55.000 --> 12:00.000
The second side of this interaction is asked by default.

12:00.000 --> 12:06.000
However, if you really want to use charisma to improve the quality of your own life,

12:06.000 --> 12:10.000
you must always remember that this concept is relative.

12:10.000 --> 12:16.000
Every time you want to influence someone, you must understand that this audience,

12:16.000 --> 12:21.000
even if it is just one person, can be very different from another.

12:21.000 --> 12:31.000
The words you use to influence the qualities you need to influence a young girl

12:31.000 --> 12:37.000
are completely different from the qualities you need to influence a graduate professor.

12:37.000 --> 12:39.000
But in general.

12:39.000 --> 12:44.000
Although, of course, there are some basic things that affect everyone.

12:44.000 --> 12:46.000
We will return to them a little later.

12:46.000 --> 12:57.000
So, try to imagine what qualities you need to influence your colleagues.

12:57.000 --> 13:03.000
Those people who do not obey you directly and those who cannot command you.

13:03.000 --> 13:17.000
Try to write down 2-3 qualities that can enhance your ability to influence them.

13:17.000 --> 13:29.000
Now draw a line and write down 2-3 qualities that will allow you to effectively influence

13:29.000 --> 13:34.000
an audience like 4-year-old children in a kindergarten.

13:34.000 --> 13:42.000
Compare the results.

13:42.000 --> 13:49.000
After that, compare how similar the 2-3 qualities you wrote down in the first and second case turned out to be.

13:49.000 --> 13:53.000
Most likely, there will be no 100% match.

13:53.000 --> 13:55.000
It seems to me.

13:56.000 --> 14:04.000
So, every time you want to gain the ability to influence an audience,

14:04.000 --> 14:07.000
it is important for you to clearly understand what kind of audience it is.

14:07.000 --> 14:09.000
Describe it clearly.

14:09.000 --> 14:16.000
Of course, over time, when you train, you will be able to do it faster and more unconsciously.

14:16.000 --> 14:24.000
But at least in the beginning, in order to use this tool effectively and to its intended purpose,

14:24.000 --> 14:27.000
you need to go through certain stages.

14:27.000 --> 14:32.000
At the end, we will give you a complete algorithm, we will derive it in a clear form.

14:32.000 --> 14:37.000
But now remember, the most important thing before you start influencing someone,

14:37.000 --> 14:40.000
you need to understand who exactly you want to influence now.

14:40.000 --> 14:46.000
And what unique qualities this community, this audience, describes.

14:46.000 --> 14:54.000
So, the second characteristic of charisma that we must constantly remember is its relativity.

14:54.000 --> 15:04.000
If you want, try to look at what will be the difference between you and such audiences as,

15:05.000 --> 15:10.000
for example, scientists at the International Conference on Sociobiology

15:12.000 --> 15:18.000
and miners with helmets sitting on a stone bridge and knocking on them.

15:18.000 --> 15:24.000
There is another characteristic of charisma, the basic characteristic of which I highlight,

15:24.000 --> 15:27.000
this is its multifacetedness.

15:28.000 --> 15:36.000
We already touched on this a little when we talked about the fact that different qualities can be required for different audiences.

15:36.000 --> 15:42.000
So, a huge number of factors affect each of the audiences.

15:42.000 --> 15:48.000
When we study this issue in training, lists of 20, 30, 40 items appear.

15:48.000 --> 15:50.000
And this is not the limit.

15:50.000 --> 15:56.000
You can continue this list indefinitely,

15:56.000 --> 16:02.000
practically describe the characteristics of a personality that help it influence other people.

16:02.000 --> 16:06.000
However, we can structure the list a little,

16:06.000 --> 16:10.000
and combine them into several important groups.

16:10.000 --> 16:16.000
So, the first group is the most obvious, it is professional qualities.

16:16.000 --> 16:22.000
If a person is a specialist, then along with other people who work in this specialty,

16:22.000 --> 16:24.000
use this skill.

16:24.000 --> 16:28.000
If he has this skill well, he will be respected.

16:28.000 --> 16:32.000
If he has a bad personality, he will be criticized.

16:32.000 --> 16:36.000
If he has this skill well, he will be respected.

16:36.000 --> 16:40.000
That is, he will have the opportunity to convince, at least.

16:40.000 --> 16:44.000
So, if we talk about the ability to convince,

16:44.000 --> 16:48.000
then we need to have at least professional competence.

16:50.000 --> 16:56.000
The second group is something that professional competence cannot be realized without.

16:56.000 --> 16:58.000
This is the ability to communicate.

16:58.000 --> 17:02.000
If a person knows how to do it, knows how to do it right, but is not able to express it,

17:02.000 --> 17:06.000
is not able to tell people about it,

17:06.000 --> 17:10.000
then he will not even be able to realize his ability to convince.

17:10.000 --> 17:14.000
If a person knows how to communicate well,

17:14.000 --> 17:18.000
knows the basic laws of social interaction between people,

17:18.000 --> 17:22.000
understands how to build his speech, where to start, where to end,

17:22.000 --> 17:28.000
at what point it is better to send a call to the audience,

17:28.000 --> 17:32.000
then he will be able to lead.

17:32.000 --> 17:36.000
And the third group of factors is behavior.

17:36.000 --> 17:40.000
A person must behave like a leader.

17:40.000 --> 17:44.000
He must be perceived as a leader, he must be like him.

17:44.000 --> 17:48.000
Here, of course, we will take confidence in ourselves

17:48.000 --> 17:56.000
and the algorithms that a person uses when communicating with other people.

17:56.000 --> 17:58.000
How does he behave?

17:58.000 --> 18:04.000
How to behave correctly, you need to work separately

18:04.000 --> 18:08.000
and look at the next point of our work

18:08.000 --> 18:12.000
how, by what laws, you need to behave correctly.

18:12.000 --> 18:18.000
So, the third property of charisma sounds like multifacetedness.

18:18.000 --> 18:26.000
And charisma is a simple sum of all the factors that exist.

18:26.000 --> 18:32.000
Of course, not a single person is able to have all the properties that are possible.

18:32.000 --> 18:34.000
In principle, this is impossible.

18:34.000 --> 18:41.000
However, we can work purposefully and consciously on the development of each of these qualities.

18:41.000 --> 18:48.000
Try to write down for yourself the qualities that you consider the most important from your target audience.

18:48.000 --> 18:54.000
For example, for your loved ones, for your family, or for your boss.

18:54.000 --> 18:58.000
And then, according to each of these qualities, I assure you,

18:58.000 --> 19:05.000
there are certain methods, books, literature, coaches, teachers

19:05.000 --> 19:08.000
that will help you develop this quality.

19:08.000 --> 19:17.000
And so, by working on each of the qualities separately, you increase the total amount of your charisma.

19:17.000 --> 19:25.000
As a result, your ability to influence other people through positive social motivation becomes higher.

19:25.000 --> 19:31.000
As a result, you will be able to persuade and lead much better.

19:31.000 --> 19:35.000
So, we have drawn up three main properties of charisma.

19:35.000 --> 19:38.000
First, it is its dual nature.

19:38.000 --> 19:43.000
In order to be charismatic, you need to be able to persuade and lead.

19:43.000 --> 19:47.000
We found out that charisma is a relative concept.

19:47.000 --> 19:51.000
And in order to find out whether this ability exists or not,

19:51.000 --> 19:57.000
you need to ask the subject and the object, the actor and his target audience.

19:57.000 --> 20:02.000
And we found out that charisma is a multifactorial concept.

20:03.000 --> 20:07.000
Now, when we have both functional and structural definitions of charisma,

20:07.000 --> 20:13.000
we can try to create a model of this phenomenon,

20:13.000 --> 20:21.000
on the basis of which we will be able to or will try to predict our own behavior

20:21.000 --> 20:27.000
and find out what qualities, what factors and how to apply them

20:27.000 --> 20:34.000
so that your ability to influence people grows and increases.

20:34.000 --> 20:41.000
So, psychology tells us that a person often acts unconsciously,

20:41.000 --> 20:49.000
that most of the actions of a person are determined by those ancient behavioral structures

20:49.000 --> 20:57.000
that were embedded in him by nature for many millennia of his development.

20:57.000 --> 21:07.000
For a very long time, people lived, pro-people, lived in the form of certain flocks.

21:07.000 --> 21:11.000
These flocks had a certain social organization.

21:11.000 --> 21:15.000
And this social organization has been preserved for millennia,

21:16.000 --> 21:19.000
thus being recorded in our ancient memory.

21:19.000 --> 21:25.000
How were these primary primitive communities arranged?

21:25.000 --> 21:34.000
If we look at the existing flocks of primates today,

21:34.000 --> 21:39.000
the flock of chimpanzees will be the closest to the pro-human flock.

21:39.000 --> 21:44.000
It consists of the following parts.

21:44.000 --> 21:50.000
There are many children who are raised together.

21:50.000 --> 21:54.000
There are several females who make up the harem.

21:54.000 --> 22:01.000
And there is the main male, the supreme leader of this community.

22:01.000 --> 22:05.000
A large adult male.

22:05.000 --> 22:09.000
There are no other adult males in this community.

22:09.000 --> 22:20.000
As the boys grow up, when they reach puberty, they are driven out of this community, from this flock.

22:20.000 --> 22:25.000
And so there is a clear division into three levels.

22:25.000 --> 22:30.000
This is the alpha male, the supreme dominant in this community.

22:30.000 --> 22:38.000
These are the beta females, those who occupy the second layer in the hierarchy.

22:38.000 --> 22:48.000
And the gamma males, those who do nothing, do not solve anything, and their main task is to grow.

22:48.000 --> 22:54.000
Look at the roles distributed in this community.

22:54.000 --> 23:03.000
Almost all the leadership is concentrated in the hands of the alpha male.

23:04.000 --> 23:12.000
He performs a very important function for his flock.

23:12.000 --> 23:16.000
And for this, the flock is completely subordinate to him.

23:18.000 --> 23:32.000
Over time, when some events occur, the male turns on and saves, protects his flock from external threats.

23:32.000 --> 23:36.000
He also organizes so that the flock does not die of hunger.

23:36.000 --> 23:40.000
His task is to get food or organize the food production.

23:40.000 --> 23:46.000
His task is to ensure that the individuals inside the flock do not quarrel.

23:46.000 --> 23:53.000
So that the conflicts that arise inside end well.

23:53.000 --> 24:01.000
In fact, he is the supreme judge and distributor of those material benefits that the flock has.

24:02.000 --> 24:14.000
If the flock needs to make an important decision, it is he who decides what decision will be made and where the flock will go.

24:14.000 --> 24:19.000
Is it time to go to the winter camp? Is it time to make supplies?

24:19.000 --> 24:25.000
Do you need to move to the other side of the river or stay in the same place?

24:25.000 --> 24:27.000
All this is decided by the alpha male.

24:27.000 --> 24:31.000
As a result, a very interesting construction is obtained.

24:31.000 --> 24:40.000
In order for this system to work, all members of the flock must unconditionally submit to the alpha male.

24:40.000 --> 24:48.000
If they do not obey him 100%, then this will worsen the possibilities of this community for survival.

24:48.000 --> 24:52.000
If the decision is made, it must be executed without prejudice.

24:52.000 --> 24:57.000
Any doubts reduce the possibility of the flock for survival.

24:57.000 --> 25:05.000
If the alpha male says that he needs to go to the other side of the river, and the flock remains on the same bank,

25:05.000 --> 25:14.000
or just stayed for a while, it is already deprived of the protection of the alpha male and can be eaten by other predators.

25:15.000 --> 25:30.000
If the alpha male organized a group hunting, but some hunters did not listen to him and left the places where they were assigned,

25:30.000 --> 25:40.000
then the prey can run out through these holes in the hunting structure and the flock can be left without food.

25:40.000 --> 25:45.000
Accordingly, the chances of survival are worsened.

25:45.000 --> 25:50.000
Therefore, only those flocks survived as a result of the long evolution,

25:50.000 --> 26:00.000
in which all individuals who are not alpha males took over the alpha male unconditionally, without discussion.

26:00.000 --> 26:07.000
Fortunately or unfortunately, this ancient construct is present in us.

26:08.000 --> 26:11.000
Thus, it turns out a very interesting thing.

26:11.000 --> 26:19.000
If we see in someone a certain quality of this primitive alpha male,

26:19.000 --> 26:25.000
we want to obey him without any doubt, without any criticism.

26:25.000 --> 26:30.000
We want to believe him. We begin to trust him absolutely instinctively.

26:30.000 --> 26:35.000
So, our model definition at this stage sounds like this.

26:35.000 --> 26:39.000
The one who looks like a father has charisma.

26:39.000 --> 26:49.000
Before we write these signs, let's remember again what functions the father performs in such a flock.

26:49.000 --> 26:55.000
The first and most important function is that he protects his flock.

26:55.000 --> 27:02.000
The second and no less important function is that he provides food and resources.

27:02.000 --> 27:06.000
The third function is that he judges and distributes.

27:06.000 --> 27:11.000
He does not allow conflicts to enter, which could end badly.

27:11.000 --> 27:15.000
He is the highest justice.

27:15.000 --> 27:17.000
He will decide.

27:17.000 --> 27:23.000
And the fourth, the last and most important function,

27:23.000 --> 27:32.000
which is performed by a leader in any community and a father in any flock, is to direct.

27:32.000 --> 27:38.000
He directs the flock. He decides where and who will go.

27:38.000 --> 27:41.000
The community has a goal.

27:41.000 --> 27:43.000
These are the four main functions.

27:44.000 --> 27:49.000
Now let's see how the father performed these functions.

27:49.000 --> 27:53.000
What qualities allowed him to do it well.

27:53.000 --> 27:55.000
So, high growth.

27:55.000 --> 28:01.000
I think that it is not necessary to explain how the physical strength allows you to perform all four functions.

28:01.000 --> 28:10.000
It is especially important for distribution, so that no one has the desire to redistribute the production.

28:10.000 --> 28:20.000
In addition to strength, a person who claims to perform the highest function should be healthy.

28:20.000 --> 28:25.000
We can give a lot of examples of very strong people, but not very healthy.

28:25.000 --> 28:32.000
It should be noted that in the charismatic influence, this is reflected quite strongly.

28:32.000 --> 28:37.000
People tend to leave the function of persuasion to not very healthy people.

28:37.000 --> 28:41.000
These are the so-called patriarchs.

28:41.000 --> 28:50.000
Any developed community contains such people in order to receive wise advice from them.

